  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Will the Indian customs department charge customs tax for a Rs90,000 DSLR camera bought in the USA?",
  "response": "Yes, the Indian Customs Department is likely to charge customs duty on a DSLR camera bought in the USA and brought into India, even if it costs Rs 90,000. Here's what you need to know:\n\n1. **Customs Duty Applicability**: India imposes customs duty on electronic goods, including cameras, when imported from abroad. The duty is calculated based on the declared value of the item, shipping costs, and insurance (CIF value).\n\n2. **Duty Rates**: The customs duty on cameras typically includes:\n   - Basic Customs Duty (BCD): Around 10% (subject to change based on current policies).\n   - Integrated Goods and Services Tax (IGST): 18% on the total value (CIF + BCD).\n   - Social Welfare Surcharge: 10% of the BCD.\n\n3. **Exemption Limit**: If the camera is for personal use and brought in by a passenger returning to India, there is an exempted duty-free allowance of \u20b950,000 (for Indian residents) under the **Transfer of Residence (ToR)** rules. However, if the value exceeds this limit, customs duty will apply to the amount above \u20b950,000.\n\n4. **Documentation**: Ensure you have the original invoice and other relevant documents to prove the value of the camera. Undervaluing the item can lead to penalties.\n\n5. **Online Purchase**: If the camera is purchased online and shipped to India, customs duty will almost certainly be levied, and the importer (you or the courier company) will need to pay it before delivery.\n\nTo estimate the duty, you can use the CIF value (Rs 90,000 + shipping + insurance) and apply the duty rates mentioned above. For precise calculations, check the latest customs duty rates on the Indian Customs website or consult a customs broker.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
